###1812
<div style="width:80%;float:left">
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/bermuda/1003.jpg" style="width:98%" />
<p style="font-size:smaller">
THE EARLIEST RECORDED(?) BERMUDA POSTAL CHARGE - 1st YEAR OF OFFICIAL P.O. - INCOMING SHIP LETTER; 
21 Aug. 1812 EL (overall light toning but sound) from "London" addressed to "Messrs. Wadson *& Astwood, Bermuda" being endorsed "P. [Ship] Catherine"; the letter would have reached the island in Sept./Nov. 1812 at which time the short-lived First Official P.O. Act was in operation (it as declared illegal by London within a year!). There is the very first incoming Bermuda Ship Letter charge of "1/3d" (triple rate) changed to "10d" (double rate) all in red crayon on the front, which fits exactly the Bermuda 1st P.O. Act charges (see full text of the Act in Ludington, esp. Article 3 ref. incoming Ship Letters, on p.112). We have not traced any other incoming Ship Letters of this early period (1812), so this may therefore be the earliest recorded Postage Due charge and, indeed the earliest postal marking of any kind, for Bermuda. There were no Bermuda P.O.
handstamps until 1820. Important Early P.O. charged cover. 
